<ITEM>HURSTE, <HI>Mi&s;s;</HI> her &s;tory, a proof of the indelicacy and indi&s;|cretion of a Lady's giving way to fir&s;t impre&s;&s;ions, v. 123. Thinks her&s;elf, becau&s;e of the inferior under&s;tanding of the man &s;he &s;uddenly <HI>fell in Love with</HI> (as it is called), and married, under obligation to every one who took but civil notice of him, v. 123, 124.</ITEM>
