<ITEM>WALDEN, <HI>Mr.</HI> an Oxford &s;tudent, his character, i. 52. His &s;upercilious behaviour to Sir Hargrave Pollexfen, i. 55. 58. Admi|red by Mr. Singleton, i. 60. Compels Mi&s;s Byron to enter into a di&s;pute about Learning and Languages, i. 63, &amp; &s;eq. A mere Stu|dent, and of no account in the Univer&s;ity, i. 65. Sneers at Mr. Addi&s;on, i. 73. His opinion of Skake&s;peare, and the Moderns when compared with the Antients; and propo&s;al for introducing the Spartan jacket for the Ladies, i. 78 Mi&s;s Byron &s;uppo&s;es him in the cha|racter of Pa&s;quin writing her character to his Mar&s;orio, i. 92, &amp; &s;eq. This debate ob&s;erved upon by Sir Charles Grandi&s;on, who thinks the cau&s;e of Learning &s;uffered in Mr. Walden's hands, vi. 357. 359. 364.</ITEM>
